hook.real_world_problem:
Swiggy processes 10 million orders a month. When a user places an order, these things need to happen:

```
1. Order saved to database
2. Restaurant notified (SMS + app push)
3. Delivery partner assigned
4. User gets confirmation SMS
5. Analytics event recorded
6. Loyalty points calculated
7. Inventory updated
8. Fraud check logged
```

**With synchronous REST calls (Module 15 approach):**
```java
// order-service.placeOrder() — the caller waits for EVERYTHING:
void placeOrder(OrderRequest req) {
    orderRepo.save(req);                    // 20ms
    restaurantClient.notify(req);           // 150ms — wait
    deliveryClient.assignDriver(req);       // 200ms — wait
    smsClient.sendConfirmation(req);        // 180ms — wait
    analyticsClient.logEvent(req);          // 100ms — wait
    loyaltyClient.calculatePoints(req);     // 90ms — wait
    // Total: 740ms before user gets response!
    // If SMS service is down → ORDER FAILS!
}
```

**With Apache Kafka (event-driven):**
```java
// order-service.placeOrder() — publishes event and returns:
void placeOrder(OrderRequest req) {
    Order saved = orderRepo.save(req);      // 20ms
    kafka.send("order-events", saved);      // 5ms — fire and forget
    return saved;                           // 25ms total!
}

// Each service listens independently:
@KafkaListener(topics="order-events") restaurantService.onOrder(order){...}
@KafkaListener(topics="order-events") deliveryService.onOrder(order){...}
@KafkaListener(topics="order-events") smsService.onOrder(order){...}
@KafkaListener(topics="order-events") analyticsService.onOrder(order){...}
// All run in parallel. SMS down? Others still work. 25ms response time.
```

25ms vs 740ms. Decoupled. Resilient. This is Kafka.

